  "opinion": "I've spent decades cleaning offices and schools in Los Angeles, and I've noticed how science is often taught in ways that don't fit everyone. My own kids, who are both in school, have been told they're 'not cut out for science' because they don't do the traditional math-heavy projects. That's a problem. The gender gap in science isn't just about women not being interested—it's about how we set up the system from the start. When I was a kid, my parents didn't push me into science, but I did it anyway because I loved fixing things. Now, I see that many girls are discouraged from science because they're told it's 'too hard' or 'not for them.' We should address this by making science more accessible and relatable. Instead of focusing on complex equations, we should show how science connects to everyday life—like how video games use physics or how cycling improves your health through biomechanics. If we do that, more people will see science as something they can do, not just something they're 'good' at. I'm depressed a lot these days, and I worry that if we don't fix this, fewer people will get the chance to explore their curiosity. But the good news is that change starts small: if a teacher says, 'You can do this,' instead of 'You're not good at this,' then maybe someone will try. Let's make science work for everyone, not just the ones who already fit the mold.",
